# Vertical-template — .cursorrules
# Single-file legacy rule set. Read by Cursor at the start of every session.
# Complements .cursor/rules/*.mdc (scoped/conditional rules).
#
# When this file conflicts with a .cursor/rules/*.mdc file, the more specific
# (glob-scoped) rule wins. When in doubt, read both.
#
# ─── PROJECT ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# This is the vertical-template repo: a multi-tenant-ready MERN starter
# for very small businesses, opinionated by business type (vertical).
#
# The full thesis lives in three project briefs at docs/:
#   - platform-concept-brief.html        (what & why)
#   - template-architecture-brief.html   (seams & decisions)
#   - visual-system-brief.html           (theme registry)
#
# The implementation playbook lives at docs/prompts/phase-N-*.html.
# The README is docs/README.html.
#
# When asked to do anything non-trivial, open the relevant brief and the
# current phase prompt FIRST. Do not infer from filenames; the docs say
# what the system means.
#
# ─── ABSOLUTE RULES ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. SINGLE TENANT CONTEXT SEAM.
#    Every Express route reads tenant context through getSiteConfig(req).
#    No process.env.TENANT_ID in route handlers. No direct imports of
#    the SiteConfig singleton in feature packs. One function, one entry.
#
# 2. TENANTID ON EVERY MODEL.
#    Every Mongoose schema declares tenantId, indexed compound with its
#    natural key. Single-tenant value is 'default' — never omit the field.
#
# 3. DUAL TYPE FILES STAY IN SYNC.
#    client/src/types/site-config.ts and server/src/types/site-config.ts
#    must be byte-identical. Same for theme-tokens.ts. The contract:check
#    script runs in CI. Editing one means editing both.
#
# 4. PAYMENTS GO THROUGH THE PROVIDER ABSTRACTION.
#    No `import Stripe from 'stripe'` and no `import { Client } from
#    'square'` outside server/src/providers/. Routes call
#    getPaymentProvider() — they don't know which provider is active.
#
# 5. THEME VALUES COME FROM CSS VARIABLES.
#    Token values are emitted by resolveTokens() into :root as CSS custom
#    properties. Hardcoded hexes, rems, or spacings outside client/src/theme/
#    are a build error. Use var(--color-brand-primary), not '#b8451f'.
#
# 6. CLIENT BUILDS DO NOT EDIT CORE CODE.
#    Per-tenant divergence is Type C — site.config.ts, site.theme.ts,
#    Custom*.tsx files. Editing feature packs, types, the resolver, or
#    middleware in a client-build branch is forbidden. The fix is either
#    to generalize the change into core or to reject it.
#
# 7. TWO-OR-MORE-VERTICALS TEST.
#    Before generalizing any feature into core, ask: would a second
#    vertical use this? If yes, it's core. If no, it's tenant config or
#    a Custom*.tsx. There is no third option.
#
# 8. DOCS UPDATE WITH CODE.
#    Every PR either (a) is fully covered by existing docs, (b) updates
#    the relevant context/prompt/brief in the same PR, or (c) opens an
#    explicit follow-up issue flagged in CHANGELOG. See
#    docs/rules/documentation-maintenance.html.
#
# ─── CONVENTIONS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Match the agency-app (askanddeliverwebapp) pattern when there's a choice.
# Workspace -> tenant. Lead -> IntakeSubmission. Cloudinary upload pattern
# unchanged. Stripe Payment Links unchanged.
#
# TypeScript strict. No `any` without a justification comment. Prefer
# `unknown` + narrowing. Use zod for runtime validation of anything
# crossing the network or hydrating from Mongo.
#
# Imports rooted at @/ on both sides. Group: external -> @/types ->
# @/features -> local.
#
# Comment WHY, not WHAT. Reference the brief that motivated a non-obvious
# choice: `// see template-architecture-brief §03 — single seam for phase 2`.
#
# ─── WORKFLOW ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Big changes (new file at top level, new dependency, new feature pack,
# schema migration): propose in chat first. Wait for approval. Then code.
#
# Small changes (within an existing file or feature pack, no new shape):
# go ahead, show the diff.
#
# When stuck, return to the brief. The briefs explain decisions that
# previous-Claude already worked through; re-reading them is faster than
# re-deriving them.
#
# ─── VERSIONING ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Template repo uses semver in CHANGELOG.md. Bump before each tagged release.
# Doc set versions independently in docs/README.html (v0.X.Y in header).
# Brief revisions bump the doc set and add a "thesis" CHANGELOG entry.
#
# See docs/rules/documentation-maintenance.html for which doc must update
# on which kind of change.
#
# ─── FORBIDDEN ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Tailwind. Next.js. SSR frameworks. GraphQL. Prisma. Monorepo tooling
# (Nx/Turbo/pnpm workspaces). Adding any of these requires a brief
# revision, not a chat decision.
#
# Reaching into another tenant's data. Even in single-tenant mode, no
# query may be written that would break under multi-tenancy — all queries
# filter on tenantId.
#
# Inventing new SiteConfig top-level fields without updating the type
# definition AND the dual-file contract. Same for ThemeTokens.
#
# Adding a new color, font, or block style by hardcoding it instead of
# registering it. The visual brief's "register before second use" rule
# is absolute.
